We find that our constrained models perform competitively compared to a standard unconstrained BERT classifier when trained and evaluated on the same dataset, while additionally providing a model whose behavior can be understood in terms of relevant symptoms in specific posts.
However, dataset-transfer evaluations demonstrate substantial degradation in BERT's effectiveness. In this setting, our constrained models outperform the unconstrained BERT and show improved generalizability, even across similar datasets.